article.headline: Wake Forest 75, N.C. Central 58
article.story: WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- L.D. Williams didn't like the way Wake Forest played, and he knows his former coach wouldn't have liked it, either. Williams scored 14 points, but the Demon Deacons allowed North Carolina Central to cut deep into their 27-point lead before coasting to a 75-58 victory over the Eagles on Monday night. "The man up in the banner watches us every game," Williams said, referring to a picture of the late Skip Prosser that hangs from the rafters at Joel Coliseum. "I know he's turning in his grave right now because the way we played defense was terrible. Give credit to N.C. Central, but for them to shoot that well against our caliber of team is definitely unacceptable. "We've just got to keep doing what we did to get us the 20-point lead, but do it harder in the second half," he added. "Once we start doing that, we'll get in the Top 25." Jamie Skeen added 13 points and James Johnson had 12 for the Demon Deacons (2-0), who never trailed but were outscored 35-29 in the second half of Dino Gaudio's second victory as their coach. Wake Forest, which had nine days off following its Nov. 9 season-opening victory over Fairfield, shot 46 percent but had trouble from long distance, making just 4-of-21 attempts from 3-point range and missing all but one of their six second-half shots from beyond the arc. "We were shooting too many 3s," Gaudio said. "We've got to get some inside scoring somehow." The Demon Deacons led by 23 points at the break and then seemed to lose focus, allowing N.C. Central to pull as close as 16 in the second half -- most recently when Philip Branch's basket with about 7 minutes left made it 64-48. "For us, moral victories are what we need in spots," N.C. Central coach Henry Dickerson said. "We're never going to dominate a game, but there are going to be stretches where if our young men will continue to play hard and execute, sometimes things fall your way." Joshua Worthy had 16 points, one-time football player Charles Futrell had 14 and Bryan Ayala scored 11 for the Eagles (0-5), who set a season high in scoring despite playing their fifth road game in an 11-day span. The first-year Division I program's brutal stretch included routs at No. 13 Duke, at No. 25 Florida and, two days earlier, at North Dakota State. During the road trek, N.C. Central -- which has just seven players on scholarship -- allowed three opponents to score at least 100 points, failed to score more than 56 in any previous game and averaged 22 turnovers. "We didn't have our legs under us when we played" at North Dakota State, Dickerson said. "We're struggling, and it's a tough, long process." Early on, they were no match for a Wake Forest program that under Gaudio has rededicated itself to defense. The Eagles turned it over on their first four trips down the court, and at one point late in the half had as many turnovers (15) as points. Jeff Teague's running jumper from the left baseline at the buzzer gave the Demon Deacons a 46-23 halftime lead, their largest advantage of the half. But that defense waned late -- they allowed the Eagles to shoot 54 percent in the second half. "Everybody knows that L.D. plays D. I know I'm not happy with it, and I know the other guys in the locker room that sit beside me every day are not happy with it," Williams said.
